{"questionId":"12518","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A sphere with diameter 3 474 000 metres can model the shape of the Moon.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Write your answer to<strong> part (b)</strong> in the form&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"a \\times {10^k}\">\n  <mi>a</mi>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mn>10</mn>\n      <mi>k</mi>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, where 1&nbsp;≤ <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"a\">\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span> &lt; 10 , <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k \\in \\mathbb{Z}\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>1.09&nbsp;× 10<sup>4</sup>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)<em>(A1)</em>(ft)<em>&nbsp; (C2)</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Follow through from part (b) only. Award <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong> for 1.09, and <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong> × 10<sup>4</sup>. Award <em><strong>(A0)(A0)</strong></em> for answers of the type: 10.9&nbsp;× 10<sup>3</sup>.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>","meta":{"questionId":"12518","referenceCode":"19M.1.SL.TZ2.T_1c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Write your answer to part (b) in the form a × 10 k , where 1 ≤ a < 10 , k ∈ Z .","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Prior learning","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.1—Using standard form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}